const PHASE_REQUIREMENTS = {
  name:"Phase 1 · Requirements",id:"req",icon:"📋",phase:"Requirements",color:"#6b7280",
  sizes:["small","medium","large","hyper"],
  short:"Quantify everything before deciding anything -- numbers are the architecture's foundation",
  detail:{
    what:"The requirements phase is the translation layer between business dreams and engineering reality. When someone says 'build a chat app,' this phase converts that into concrete, measurable constraints: '1M DAU, p99 200ms, 99.95% uptime, $50K/mo budget, EU + US users, 80% mobile, 30:1 read/write ratio, 500GB initial data growing 50GB/month.' It covers seven critical dimensions: (1) traffic patterns -- how much load, when, from where; (2) latency targets -- how fast each endpoint must respond, measured at the 99th percentile, not averages; (3) availability targets -- how much downtime is tolerable, priced in nines; (4) consistency needs -- which operations must see the latest data vs. can tolerate staleness; (5) geographic distribution -- where users are and where data must legally reside; (6) data growth -- how fast storage needs scale and when you'll hit physical limits; and (7) budget -- how much you can spend monthly and what that buys in cloud resources. Think of these numbers as GPS coordinates for your architecture: without them, every downstream decision is a guess. With them, each decision becomes justifiable, debatable, and reversible for the right reasons.",
    why:"Every architectural choice is only correct relative to your actual workload -- there is no universally 'right' architecture. PostgreSQL is the perfect database at 1,000 RPS and a dangerous choice at 1,000,000 RPS; Cassandra is the opposite. A monolith is ideal for 5 engineers and a bottleneck for 500. Redis is perfect for hot data and a money pit for cold data. Without concrete numbers, you're choosing architectures based on blog posts, conference talks, and what Netflix does -- none of which apply to your specific situation. Guessing wrong is catastrophically expensive in both directions: an over-engineered architecture (microservices for a 3-person team, Cassandra for 100GB of data) wastes money and slows development for years as engineers fight unnecessary complexity. An under-engineered one (single Postgres for 10M concurrent users) collapses on launch day. Requirements also serve as the social contract between engineering and product/business: they make trade-offs visible and negotiable. When you tell a product manager '99.99% uptime costs 5× more than 99.9% -- which do you want?', you're preventing the implicit assumption that everything should be perfect, which leads to either crushing cost or devastating disappointment. The requirements document is the single artifact that prevents the most expensive type of engineering mistake: building the right thing for the wrong scale, or the wrong thing for the right scale.",
    numbers:"Spend 20–30% of your design time here -- it feels slow, but a poorly specified system gets designed twice (once wrong, once right). Key numbers to nail down before sketching any architecture: (1) average and peak RPS -- and their ratio (typically 3–10× for consumer, 5–10× for B2B SaaS, 50–100× for seasonal e-commerce); (2) read/write ratio -- determines whether you optimize with caches+replicas or sharding+async; (3) p99 latency target per endpoint class -- not a single global number; (4) availability SLO -- priced in nines with explicit allowed downtime per month; (5) data size today + growth per month -- extrapolate to 3 years to understand when you'll hit tier thresholds; (6) geographic distribution of users -- drives CDN, multi-region, and data residency decisions; (7) consistency requirements per feature -- 'bank balance' needs strong, 'like count' can be eventual. If any of these aren't pinned within an order of magnitude, you're not ready to start designing. A useful technique: write down your best guess, then ask 'what changes in the architecture if this number is 10× higher or 10× lower?' If the answer is 'nothing,' the number doesn't matter enough to nail down. If the answer is 'everything,' you must nail it down before proceeding."
  },
  tradeoffs:[{axis:"Precision vs Speed",left:"Perfect spec → slow start, but correct direction",right:"Fast start → wrong design, expensive rewrites later",pos:0.4}],
  pitfalls:[
    {name:"Designing for hypothetical scale",desc:"'What if we go viral and hit 100M users?' This question has killed more startups than bad code. You build for 100M, ship in 18 months instead of 3, spend $2M on infrastructure that serves 5,000 users, and run out of money before product-market fit. The correct approach: design for 10× your current or projected scale, not 10,000×. This gives you headroom for success while keeping you fast and lean. When you actually approach your ceiling, you'll have revenue, a team, and real data to inform the redesign. Instagram had 13 employees when acquired for $1B -- they didn't design for a billion users on day one. They scaled iteratively as they grew."},
    {name:"Single SLO across all endpoints",desc:"You set 'p99 <200ms' globally for the entire API. But /search absolutely needs that speed because users are waiting, while /export-pdf is a background job that can take 30 seconds and nobody cares. /health-check should be <10ms. /admin/reconciliation can take a minute. Per-endpoint SLOs (grouped into tiers: 'interactive' at <200ms, 'fast-background' at <2s, 'batch' at <30s) let you optimize where it matters (the checkout flow) and not waste effort where it doesn't (the weekly CSV export). This also prevents the political trap where one slow endpoint drags the whole team into optimization mode when the user-facing paths are fine."},
    {name:"Treating peak as average",desc:"You quote '10K RPS' which is actually your Black Friday peak; you size infrastructure for 10K constant. Now you're paying 5× more than necessary 364 days a year. Conversely, if 10K is your average and your peak-to-average ratio is 8× (common for consumer apps with evening spikes), you'll see 80K RPS at peak and your infrastructure melts. Always specify both average AND peak, and document the peak-to-average ratio. For capacity planning, size your autoscaling floor for average, ceiling for peak + 30% headroom, and have a load shedding plan for anything beyond that."},
    {name:"Not asking about the read/write ratio",desc:"10K RPS with a 99:1 read-heavy pattern (social media feed) needs caches, CDN, and read replicas -- straightforward, well-understood infrastructure that's cheap to operate. The same 10K RPS with a 1:99 write-heavy pattern (IoT telemetry ingestion) needs write-optimized databases (LSM-tree stores like Cassandra or RocksDB), sharding, async pipelines, and potentially event sourcing -- a fundamentally different architecture that's 5× more complex. Same total RPS, opposite designs. A ratio of 10:1 (e-commerce: browsing vs buying) sits in between and benefits from both strategies. Not asking this question is like a doctor prescribing treatment without asking about symptoms."},
    {name:"Vague availability target",desc:"'The system should always be up' is not a requirement -- it's a wish. 100% uptime is physically impossible (even DNS has failed). Pin it down in nines, then connect those nines to real-world impact and cost: 99% = 7.3 hours/month of allowed downtime (fine for internal tools). 99.9% = 43 minutes/month (acceptable for most consumer apps -- users will grumble but come back). 99.95% = 22 minutes/month (standard B2B SaaS commitment). 99.99% = 4.4 minutes/month (requires multi-AZ with automated failover, circuit breakers, health-aware load balancing -- costs 3–5× more than 99.9%). 99.999% = 26 seconds/month (requires multi-region active-active, cell architecture, dedicated SRE team, chaos engineering -- costs 20–50× more than 99.9%). Each extra nine is disproportionately more expensive because it requires redundancy for the redundancy. Make the business decide: 'Do you want to pay $200K/year for 4.4 minutes of downtime, or $50K/year for 43 minutes?'"}
  ],
  examples:[
    {name:"Twitter's underestimated growth",desc:"Twitter was built in 2006 as a simple Ruby on Rails monolith with a single MySQL database, designed for 'a few thousand users posting short messages.' Within two years, it went viral and the infamous 'Fail Whale' became a cultural icon -- the site crashed constantly under load. The architecture couldn't handle the read amplification of the timeline (one tweet from a popular user creates millions of read operations). It took Twitter 3+ years of painful rewrites (Ruby → Scala/JVM, MySQL → Manhattan/Cassandra, monolith → microservices) to stabilize. The lesson isn't that they should have built for Twitter-scale on day one -- that would have been absurd. The lesson is: get the order of magnitude right. If your projected user base is 10K, design for 100K but have a clear plan for what changes at 1M. You can't refactor your way out of a 1,000× miscalculation under live traffic."},
    {name:"Discord's deliberate tiered availability",desc:"Discord explicitly designed different availability tiers for different features. Voice chat rooms target 99.9% availability, not 99.99%. Why? Because gamers will reconnect from a 30-second blip without thinking twice -- it's expected in gaming culture. Spending 3–5× more infrastructure budget for one extra nine of availability on voice (going from 99.9% to 99.99%) would have been wasted money that could go toward features. Meanwhile, their authentication and message persistence systems have stricter SLOs because losing a message or failing to authenticate is genuinely disruptive. This per-feature SLO approach is mature engineering: it allocates budget where users notice and saves it where they don't."}
  ],
  levelUp:[],
  children:[
    {name:"Traffic & Scale",id:"req-traffic",icon:"📈",phase:"Requirements",color:"#6b7280",
     sizes:["small","medium","large","hyper"],
     short:"RPS, DAU, MAU, peak-to-avg ratio -- the load your system must bear",
     detail:{
       what:"Traffic & scale metrics quantify the volume of demand your system faces. The critical numbers are: requests per second (average, p95, p99), daily/monthly active users (DAU/MAU), peak-to-average ratio (how spiky is your traffic?), data volume today, and data growth rate. These aren't just numbers -- they're the primary input to every infrastructure decision. Think of RPS as the 'weight' your system must lift: a system designed for 100 RPS is structurally different from one designed for 100K RPS, just as a bicycle bridge is structurally different from a highway bridge. You can't retrofit one into the other. Additionally, traffic is not uniform -- it has daily patterns (9am spike for B2B, 8pm spike for consumer), weekly patterns (Monday mornings for enterprise tools), seasonal patterns (Black Friday for e-commerce, tax season for financial apps), and viral spikes (a Reddit front page, a celebrity tweet, a TikTok mention). Each pattern demands different scaling strategies.",
       why:"Traffic is the primary input to nearly every infrastructure decision you'll make: how many database shards you need (1 at 1K RPS, 16 at 100K), how many read replicas (0 at low load, 5+ at high), what cache tier (none → Redis → cluster → multi-tier), what autoscaling policy (scale on CPU at 70%, scale on RPS, or pre-warm for known patterns), and what compute model (serverless for spiky, containers for steady). Get the order of magnitude wrong and your architecture is built for the wrong system entirely. Get the peak-to-average ratio wrong and you either over-provision (paying 5–10× too much 90% of the time) or melt during traffic spikes (losing revenue and users exactly when they're most engaged). Traffic estimation is also how you detect when you're approaching the next tier threshold -- that's when you need to plan your next architectural evolution, not after you've already hit the wall. Think of it like fuel gauge for infrastructure: ignore it and you run out at the worst time.",
       numbers:"Collect these metrics before any architectural decision: avg RPS, p95 RPS (your 'normal peak'), p99 RPS (your 'worst normal day'), peak-to-avg multiplier, DAU, MAU, data size today, data growth/month. Typical peak-to-avg ratios by industry: B2B SaaS 5–10× (driven by workday patterns -- 9am Monday is the universal SaaS peak), consumer social 3–5× (evening + weekend peaks), media/streaming 3–8× (primetime 7–10pm), seasonal e-commerce 50–100× (Black Friday can be 100× a normal Tuesday). Always size your steady-state infrastructure for average load with autoscaling headroom to handle peak, and have load-shedding for anything beyond planned peak. Critical formula: if your DB can handle 50K TPS and your peak is 40K, you have 20% headroom -- too thin. Aim for 40–50% headroom at peak so you can survive an unexpected spike or a cache failure without an outage."
     },
     tradeoffs:[{axis:"Design for avg vs design for peak",left:"Cheaper infra, risk of failure at peak",right:"No outage at peak, higher idle cost -- use autoscaling to split the difference",pos:0.7}],
     pitfalls:[
       {name:"Forgetting daily/weekly cycles",desc:"Average RPS is 2K and you're comfortable. But every Monday at 9am it spikes to 16K (8×) as users return from the weekend, and every evening at 8pm consumer traffic triples. If you sized for 2K, you crash at 16K. Always model the full 24h/7d traffic curve, not just averages. Use tools like Datadog or CloudWatch to visualize your actual traffic pattern over time. Many systems have a 'witching hour' -- find yours."},
       {name:"Ignoring data growth",desc:"100GB today, growing 10GB/month. In 3 years you'll have 460GB -- still comfortable for Postgres. But at 100GB/month growth rate, in 5 years you'll have 6TB, and you needed to start planning the sharding migration at year 2. Data growth is compound: storage costs increase linearly, but query performance often degrades non-linearly (a query over 6TB is not just 60× slower than over 100GB -- it can be 600× slower if indexes don't fit in memory). Project forward 3 years and plan for the architectural transitions you'll need to make."}
     ],
     examples:[
       {name:"Reddit traffic spike from a viral post",desc:"A normal subreddit might sit at 100 RPS. A post hits the front page and within 2 minutes that subreddit is getting 10,000+ RPS -- a 100× spike. Reddit handles this with a multi-layer defense: (1) aggressive CDN caching -- most viral pages are served entirely from Cloudflare's edge within seconds of going hot; (2) degraded rendering -- hot pages show cached/stale versions rather than computing live data; (3) load shedding -- if the spike exceeds all capacity, they return 503 to a percentage of users rather than letting the entire site slow to a crawl. This demonstrates a critical principle: design for known traffic patterns explicitly. Virality is predictable in shape (sudden 100× spike, sustained for 2–6 hours, then rapid decay) even if the timing isn't. Have a plan for it."}
     ],
     sizes_cfg:{
       small:{range:"<1K RPS avg, <5K peak, <1M DAU, <100GB data",rec:"At this scale, back-of-napkin math is sufficient for capacity planning. Assume 5–10× daily peak over average. A small SaaS typically hits peak at 9am–11am Monday through Friday in its primary timezone. Use a single managed server (Railway, Render, or a small EC2/GCE instance). Monitor with free-tier Datadog or CloudWatch. Don't overthink -- you'll know when you're approaching the ceiling because response times will creep up. Key technologies: Google Analytics or Mixpanel for user traffic patterns (free tier), basic server metrics (CPU, memory, disk I/O) from your hosting provider. At this scale, your bottleneck is almost always the database, not compute -- watch for slow queries using pg_stat_statements or your ORM's query logging.",tools:["Google Analytics","Mixpanel","back-of-napkin math","CloudWatch free tier"]},
       medium:{range:"1K–50K RPS avg, up to 250K peak, 1M–50M DAU, 100GB–10TB",rec:"Model your 24-hour traffic curve in detail. Identify timezone-driven peaks and weekly patterns. Use 7-day moving averages for capacity planning and alert when you exceed 60% of your provisioned capacity. You need real APM now: Datadog ($15/host/month for infra + $31/host for APM) gives you full visibility; CloudWatch is cheaper but less rich. Load test regularly with k6 (open source, scripted HTTP load generation) or Locust (Python-based, distributed). At this scale, autoscaling becomes important -- set scale-up at 60% CPU with a 2-minute cooldown, and scale-down at 30% CPU with a 10-minute cooldown (asymmetric to avoid flapping). Technology comparison: Datadog is the gold standard for visibility but expensive at scale; Prometheus+Grafana is free and powerful but requires self-hosting; NewRelic offers a generous free tier (100GB/month ingest); AWS CloudWatch is cheap but has limited querying power.",tools:["Datadog APM","CloudWatch","load testing with k6","Prometheus+Grafana"]},
       large:{range:"50K–500K RPS avg, up to 2M peak, 50M–500M DAU, 10TB–1PB",rec:"Traffic shaping becomes critical at this scale. Use token bucket rate limiting at the gateway layer (Kong, Envoy) to prevent any single client from consuming too much capacity. Model per-feature traffic separately because different features have different bottlenecks -- your /feed endpoint might be cache-bound while /search is CPU-bound and /upload is bandwidth-bound. At this tier, you need dedicated capacity planning meetings (monthly) and should be able to answer: 'At current growth rate, when will we hit the next infrastructure ceiling?' Tools: Prometheus for metrics (supports federation across clusters), Grafana for dashboards, Locust or Vegeta for distributed load testing. Key technology choices: Envoy proxy (more control and visibility, used by Lyft, Airbnb, Stripe) for traffic management vs. NGINX (difficult to configure, better raw performance). Both can handle 1M+ RPS per node when configured correctly.",tools:["Prometheus","Grafana","Locust","Vegeta","Envoy"]},
       hyper:{range:">500K RPS avg, >5M peak, >500M DAU, >1PB",rec:"Traffic is modeled per PoP (Point of Presence), per datacenter, per service. Capacity planning is a full-time team function with ML-based forecasting that predicts traffic 1–4 weeks out with <10% error. Every service publishes its own capacity metrics and owns its own scaling. Global load shedding is automated: if a datacenter approaches capacity, traffic is rerouted to the nearest healthy DC within seconds via anycast/BGP. At this scale, companies like Google use custom tools (Borg for scheduling, Borgmon for monitoring) and Facebook uses Prophet for traffic forecasting. Open-source alternatives: Envoy for traffic management at the edge, custom ML models trained on historical traffic patterns. The key mental shift: at this scale, traffic management IS the product -- a 1% efficiency gain saves millions of dollars per year.",tools:["Custom forecasting","Envoy","Global load shedding","ML capacity planning"]}
     },
     levelUp:[
       {from:"small",to:"medium",trigger:">1K RPS sustained or >1M DAU -- your single server is consistently above 60% CPU at peak",action:"Introduce horizontal scaling: containerize your application, add a load balancer (AWS ALB or Cloudflare), and separate stateless compute from stateful data (move sessions to Redis, files to S3). This is the first architectural boundary you cross."},
       {from:"medium",to:"large",trigger:">50K RPS or >50M DAU -- autoscaling can't keep up with spikes, or regional users have poor latency",action:"Add regional traffic routing via GeoDNS or global load balancer. Implement sophisticated autoscaling (scale on custom metrics like queue depth or p99 latency, not just CPU). Add CDN for static + cacheable content to serve 60–80% of requests from edge."},
       {from:"large",to:"hyper",trigger:">500K RPS or >500M DAU -- you need sub-50ms latency globally and zero single points of failure",action:"Deploy globally with anycast DNS so every user hits the nearest PoP. Per-datacenter capacity planning with automated overflow. Traffic shifting on failures within seconds. This level typically requires a dedicated infrastructure/platform team."}
     ],
     children:[]},

    {name:"Read / Write Ratio",id:"req-rw",icon:"⚖️",phase:"Requirements",color:"#6b7280",
     sizes:["small","medium","large","hyper"],
     short:"The single ratio that determines whether you need caches or shards",
     detail:{
       what:"The read/write ratio is the proportion of read operations to write operations in your workload. It's the single most important number for database architecture decisions because it determines whether your bottleneck is serving data (reads) or storing data (writes) -- and these require fundamentally different solutions. A 100:1 ratio (read-heavy) means for every write, there are 100 reads -- optimize for reading. A 1:100 ratio (write-heavy) means the opposite -- optimize for writing. Most applications are read-heavy (users browse 100× more than they post), but within a single product, different features have wildly different ratios: the social feed is 1000:1 (read-heavy), the analytics pipeline is 1:1000 (write-heavy), and the shopping cart is 5:1 (roughly balanced). Analyze per feature, not just system-wide, because each feature may need different infrastructure.",
       why:"The same 100K RPS leads to completely different architectures depending on the read/write split. A 100K RPS read-heavy system (99% reads = 99K reads/s, 1K writes/s) is solved by adding cache (Redis serves 95% of reads from memory at 0.1ms each) + read replicas (remaining cache misses hit replicas, not the primary) -- relatively straightforward infrastructure that costs maybe $2K/month. A 100K RPS write-heavy system (1% reads, 99K writes/s) is an entirely different beast: you need write-optimized databases like Cassandra or DynamoDB (which use LSM-tree storage engines designed for high write throughput), horizontal sharding across many nodes, async write pipelines (Kafka buffering writes so the DB isn't overwhelmed), and potentially event sourcing -- infrastructure that costs $20K+/month and requires specialized expertise. Same total RPS, 10× different cost and complexity. Not knowing the ratio before designing is like an architect not knowing whether a building will house an office or a warehouse -- the foundations are completely different.",
       numbers:"Typical ratios by application type: social media feed 1000:1 read-heavy (users scroll through hundreds of posts for every one they create), e-commerce product catalog 100:1 (browsing vs purchasing), SaaS dashboard 10:1, real-time chat 1:1 (send and receive roughly equally), analytics/telemetry ingestion 1:100 write-heavy (massive ingest, occasional query), IoT sensor data 1:1000 write-heavy. Within a single product, different features vary wildly -- analyze each one. The ratio also changes over time: early-stage products with few users are often more write-heavy (every user is creating data); mature products with large audiences become read-heavy (content is created by few, consumed by many -- the 1% rule of the internet)."
     },
     tradeoffs:[{axis:"Read optimization vs Write optimization",left:"More replicas, more caches, higher read throughput -- but writes only go to primary",right:"Async writes, sharding, LSM-tree stores -- higher write throughput, but reads are more complex",pos:0.5},{axis:"Consistency vs Throughput",left:"Strong reads from primary: always correct, but primary becomes bottleneck",right:"Stale reads from replica/cache: fast and scalable, but may show outdated data",pos:0.5}],
     pitfalls:[
       {name:"Average ratio hides bursty writes",desc:"Your average ratio is 100:1 -- comfortably read-heavy. But every hour, a 10-second batch import fires at a 1:10 ratio (90% writes). If your architecture is optimized for reads with a single-writer primary DB, that burst overwhelms the primary every hour. Solution: analyze the p99 ratio (what's the ratio during your busiest write period?), not just the average. If burst writes are a pattern, add a write buffer (Kafka, SQS) that absorbs the burst and drains at a sustainable rate."},
       {name:"Writes that are actually reads in disguise",desc:"You count 'page view increment' as a write -- but it's an idempotent counter that can be batched and you can tolerate losing a few. That's fundamentally different from a 'create order' write that must persist durably. Distinguish durable writes (must be persisted immediately and acknowledged -- financial transactions, user creations) from telemetry writes (can be batched, sampled, or dropped without business impact -- page views, click tracking). Architect them differently: durable writes go to your primary DB with ACID guarantees; telemetry writes go to a buffered pipeline (Kafka → aggregation → batch write to a columnar store)."}
     ],
     examples:[
       {name:"Twitter timelines -- write-heavy fan-out architecture",desc:"When a user with 1 million followers tweets, Twitter's 'fan-out on write' architecture inserts that tweet into each follower's precomputed timeline cache -- that's 1 million write operations from a single tweet. They chose this approach so that reading a timeline is a simple O(1) cache lookup (just fetch the precomputed list), making the read path blazing fast at the cost of an expensive write path. The alternative -- 'fan-out on read' -- would compute the timeline at read time by querying all followed users' recent tweets, which would be cheap to write but brutally expensive to read at their scale (each timeline view would require joining data from hundreds of followed accounts). The R/W ratio analysis drove this fundamental architectural decision: because timelines are read 1000× more often than tweets are posted, optimizing the read path is worth the write cost. For celebrity accounts with 100M+ followers, Twitter uses a hybrid approach -- they fan-out on read for these mega-accounts to avoid the write amplification."}
     ],
     sizes_cfg:{
       small:{range:"Typically <10K reads/day, <1K writes/day",rec:"Don't optimize yet -- premature optimization is the root of all evil at this scale. Use a single PostgreSQL instance. It handles mixed read/write workloads beautifully up to ~50K TPS on good hardware. Add read replicas only when you see p99 read latency consistently >200ms or DB CPU consistently >70%. At small scale, the ratio doesn't matter much because everything fits in memory. Key technologies: PostgreSQL (the default choice for 99% of applications at this scale -- it's ACID-compliant, has excellent tooling, and the ecosystem is massive), SQLite (surprisingly capable for read-heavy single-server apps, used by many mobile apps and Pieter Levels' entire portfolio of products).",tools:["Postgres","SQLite"]},
       medium:{range:"Millions of reads/day, hundreds of thousands of writes",rec:"If ratio is >10:1 (read-heavy): add 1–2 read replicas to offload reads from the primary. Use PgBouncer for connection pooling (Postgres has a hard limit of ~500 concurrent connections; PgBouncer can multiplex 5,000 application connections into 50 DB connections). Add Redis (ElastiCache or self-hosted) for caching the top 20% of data that serves 80% of reads. If ratio is <1:10 (write-heavy): investigate connection pooling (PgBouncer), async writes via a message queue (RabbitMQ for simple task queues at ~50K msg/s, or SQS for managed simplicity at ~3K msg/s per queue), and consider whether writes can be batched. Technology comparison: PgBouncer is the gold standard for Postgres connection pooling (free, battle-tested, used by every major Postgres deployment); PgCat is a newer alternative with built-in load balancing and sharding awareness. Redis (in-memory, ~0.1ms reads) vs Memcached (simpler, slightly faster for pure key-value, but no persistence or data structures) -- Redis wins for most use cases because of its richer feature set.",tools:["PgBouncer","Redis","RabbitMQ","SQS"]},
       large:{range:"Billions of reads/day, millions of writes",rec:"Read-heavy optimization: deploy Redis Cluster (multiple shards, 100K+ ops/sec per shard, auto-failover) as your primary cache tier. Put a CDN (Cloudflare, CloudFront) in front for HTTP-cacheable responses to absorb 60–80% of reads at the edge. Use computed/materialized views for expensive aggregations. Write-heavy optimization: shard your writes across multiple DB nodes (Citus for Postgres, Vitess for MySQL). Use LSM-tree databases for write-heavy workloads: Cassandra (open source, handles 10K–100K writes/sec per node, scales linearly), ScyllaDB (Cassandra-compatible but written in C++ -- 3–10× better per-node performance), or RocksDB (embedded LSM engine used by CockroachDB and TiDB under the hood). Technology comparison: Cassandra vs ScyllaDB -- ScyllaDB is API-compatible with Cassandra but achieves 3–10× better performance per node due to C++ implementation and shard-per-core architecture; however, its community is smaller. Both handle 100K+ writes/sec per node. DynamoDB (AWS managed) is operationally simpler but more expensive at scale and locks you into AWS.",tools:["Redis Cluster","Cassandra","ScyllaDB","CDN","Kafka"]},
       hyper:{range:"Trillions of reads/day (CDN-served), petabytes written",rec:"Reads are almost entirely served by CDN edge (target cache-hit rate >95% -- at this level, 95% of user requests never reach your origin servers). For the remaining 5%, use multi-tier caching: L1 in-process (Caffeine for Java, 10μs), L2 Redis Cluster (0.5ms), L3 origin DB (5–50ms). Writes are partitioned into streams (Kafka with thousands of partitions, handling 1M+ events/sec per cluster), processed asynchronously through a pipeline (Kafka → Flink for stream processing → batch write to columnar storage like Parquet on S3), and reconciled eventually. At this scale, the 'write' path is really an 'event ingestion' path. Technologies: Kafka (LinkedIn-created, the industry standard for event streaming at 1M+ msg/sec), Apache Flink (true stream processing with exactly-once semantics, used by Alibaba, Uber, Netflix), Apache Spark Structured Streaming (good for batch-oriented stream processing). Fastly and Cloudflare are the leading CDNs for dynamic content at global scale.",tools:["Fastly","Cloudflare","Kafka","Flink","multi-tier cache"]}
     },
     levelUp:[
       {from:"small",to:"medium",trigger:"Read latency p99 >200ms or DB CPU >70% sustained, indicating the database can't serve all traffic alone",action:"Add a read replica to offload read queries. Add Redis for caching the hottest 10–20% of data (start with 30-min TTL). Analyze the slow query log (pg_stat_statements in Postgres) to find and index the worst offenders -- this alone often 2-5× your effective capacity."},
       {from:"medium",to:"large",trigger:">10M reads/day or write queue consistently growing (consumers can't keep up)",action:"Deploy Redis Cluster for high-availability caching. Introduce CQRS (Command Query Responsibility Segregation): separate the read model (optimized for queries, denormalized, cached) from the write model (normalized, ACID). This is a significant architectural shift but unlocks independent scaling of reads and writes."},
       {from:"large",to:"hyper",trigger:"Cache hit rate plateaus below 90% (working set too large for Redis) or write throughput bottlenecked despite sharding",action:"Global CDN for all cacheable HTTP responses. Write sharding with event-sourced pipeline (every write becomes an event in Kafka, consumed by multiple downstream systems -- search index, analytics, notification service -- independently). This is the architecture of Twitter, LinkedIn, and Uber at scale."}
     ],
     children:[]},

    {name:"Latency SLOs",id:"req-latency",icon:"⚡",phase:"Requirements",color:"#6b7280",
     sizes:["small","medium","large","hyper"],
     short:"p50, p99, p999 targets per endpoint -- because averages lie",
     detail:{
       what:"Service Level Objectives for response time, expressed as percentiles. p50 (median) = the experience of your 'typical' user. p99 (99th percentile) = the experience of your worst 1% -- and these are often your most active, most valuable users (power users who make many requests are statistically more likely to hit the tail). p999 (99.9th) = the experience during rare but real worst-case scenarios. These are set per endpoint or per endpoint class, because /search (interactive, user waiting) and /generate-report (background, user went to get coffee) have fundamentally different requirements. The latency budget concept is critical: if your end-to-end p99 target is 200ms, and your API gateway takes 5ms, authentication takes 10ms, and the network round-trip to the user takes 50ms, your application has only 135ms to do its work -- including any database queries, cache lookups, and downstream service calls. Every component's latency is subtracted from your budget.",
       why:"Latency directly impacts user behavior and revenue. Amazon famously measured that every 100ms of added latency cost them 1% of sales. Google found that a 500ms increase in search latency reduced traffic by 20%. For mobile users on spotty connections, the impact is even greater: 53% of mobile users abandon a page that takes >3 seconds (Google research). The latency SLO constrains your architecture more than almost any other requirement: a 10ms SLO forces data to be in memory at the edge (ruling out database round-trips entirely). A 200ms SLO allows one database round-trip but not three. A 5-second SLO allows complex computation. Without explicit targets, engineers optimize based on gut feel -- some will gold-plate a settings page to 5ms while the checkout flow languishes at 3 seconds. Per-percentile measurement matters because averages are liars: if 99 requests take 10ms and 1 takes 10 seconds, the average is 109ms -- which sounds fine but hides the fact that 1 in 100 users has a terrible experience. And that 1 in 100 isn't random -- it's often caused by cold caches, garbage collection pauses, or connection pool exhaustion, which correlate with high-load periods when you have the most users.",
       numbers:"Human perception thresholds (based on decades of HCI research): <100ms feels instant (user perceives no delay -- aim for this on keyboard input, button clicks), 100–300ms feels responsive (user notices a brief pause but flow isn't broken -- acceptable for page loads, API responses), 300ms–1s feels sluggish (user is consciously waiting -- unacceptable for interactive UI, OK for search results), >1s feels broken (user considers whether something went wrong -- only acceptable if you show a progress indicator), >3s = user leaves (53% mobile abandonment rate). Common targets by endpoint type: interactive APIs (search, feed, profile) p99 <200ms; background-triggered (send email, resize image) p99 <5s; real-time push (chat message delivery, notification) p99 <100ms; batch operations (CSV export, report generation) p99 <30s. Always measure and alert on p99, not averages. For critical paths (checkout, authentication), also measure p999."
     },
     tradeoffs:[{axis:"Strict SLO vs Cost",left:"Tighter latency targets require more infrastructure: caching, edge compute, read replicas, precomputation",right:"Looser targets allow simpler, cheaper architecture with fewer components",pos:0.6},{axis:"Consistency vs Latency (the fundamental tradeoff)",left:"Wait for quorum response from multiple DB replicas to ensure consistency -- adds 10–100ms",right:"Serve from nearest cache/replica which may be stale -- sub-millisecond but potentially outdated data",pos:0.5}],
     pitfalls:[
       {name:"Optimizing average instead of p99",desc:"'Our average latency is 50ms -- we're great!' But p99 is 5 seconds. That means 1 in 100 requests is 100× slower than the median. If a user makes 20 API calls per page load, there's an 18% chance at least one of them hits the p99 tail -- so nearly 1 in 5 page loads feels terrible. Always measure and optimize tail percentiles. Averages are mathematically useless for latency (they're dominated by the distribution shape, not the typical experience). Use histograms in Prometheus/Datadog, not averages."},
       {name:"SLO ignores network latency",desc:"Your server-side p99 is a beautiful 50ms. But the user is in Sydney and your server is in Virginia -- the speed-of-light round trip alone is ~250ms. They experience 300ms minimum no matter how fast your code is. Either deploy compute in a region near your users (ap-southeast-2 for Australia), use a CDN to serve cacheable responses from edge, or set your SLO honestly to include network: 'p99 <200ms for users within 3000km of our primary region; p99 <500ms for all other users.' Ignoring network latency in your SLO creates a gap between what you measure and what users experience."},
       {name:"Same SLO across all endpoints",desc:"Your login endpoint and your weekly-report endpoint both have a 200ms SLO. You spend engineering weeks optimizing the report endpoint (which is used by 3 people) to hit 200ms, while the search endpoint (used by 100K users/hour) is at 190ms and one bad query could push it over. Tier your endpoints: Tier 1 (login, search, checkout) = p99 <100ms; Tier 2 (profile, settings, list views) = p99 <300ms; Tier 3 (export, report, admin) = p99 <5s. Invest optimization effort proportional to tier importance × traffic volume."}
     ],
     examples:[
       {name:"Amazon's 100ms = 1% revenue finding",desc:"Internal Amazon research found that every 100ms of additional latency in their product page load time reduced sales by approximately 1%. For a company doing ~$500B/year in revenue, that's $5B per 100ms. This is why Amazon over-invests in latency infrastructure: CloudFront CDN (the world's second-largest CDN after Cloudflare), DynamoDB (single-digit millisecond reads at any scale), and custom hardware (Graviton processors, Nitro hypervisors). For your startup: the revenue impact is proportionally similar. If you do $1M/year and your checkout page is 500ms slower than it could be, you're leaving ~$50K on the table. Latency optimization isn't premature optimization -- it's revenue optimization."},
       {name:"Google's mobile 3-second rule and Core Web Vitals",desc:"Google measured that 53% of mobile users abandon a page that takes >3 seconds to load. This finding drove the creation of AMP (Accelerated Mobile Pages), the Core Web Vitals initiative (LCP, FID, CLS metrics), and ultimately affected search rankings -- Google penalizes slow sites. The engineering response: aggressive preloading, service workers for offline-first, and edge compute (Cloudflare Workers, Lambda@Edge) to run code at the network edge instead of the origin. The broader lesson: latency targets should be set based on what users will actually tolerate, not what feels acceptable to engineers on fast office connections. Test from mobile on 3G to feel what your users feel."}
     ],
     sizes_cfg:{
       small:{range:"p99 <500ms is typically acceptable for early-stage products",rec:"At small scale, 90% of latency problems are caused by slow database queries, not architectural issues. Before adding any infrastructure: (1) Enable pg_stat_statements in PostgreSQL and find your slowest queries; (2) Run EXPLAIN ANALYZE on each and add missing indexes; (3) Look for N+1 queries in your ORM (the #1 cause of slow APIs in Rails/Django/Express apps). These three steps often 5–10× your effective performance for zero infrastructure cost. Key technologies: pg_stat_statements (built into Postgres, shows cumulative query statistics -- essential), EXPLAIN ANALYZE (shows the actual execution plan including time per step), NewRelic or Datadog APM free tier (shows per-request breakdown of where time is spent: app code vs DB vs external calls).",tools:["pg_stat_statements","EXPLAIN ANALYZE","NewRelic","Datadog free tier"]},
       medium:{range:"p99 <200ms target for user-facing endpoints",rec:"Add Redis (ElastiCache or Upstash for serverless) for frequently-read data -- session data, user profiles, feature flags, computed aggregations. Use connection pooling (PgBouncer) to reduce per-connection overhead. Set query timeouts (statement_timeout = 5000 in Postgres) so a pathological query can't hold connections indefinitely. Add APM instrumentation to find latency contributors: is it the DB? The network? An external API? A slow serialization? You can't optimize what you can't measure. Technology comparison: Redis (in-memory, ~0.1ms reads, rich data structures, persistence options) is the standard choice. Memcached is slightly faster for simple key-value but lacks persistence and data structures. Dragonfly is a newer Redis-compatible in-memory store claiming 25× better throughput -- worth evaluating but less battle-tested. For APM: Datadog ($31/host/month for APM) is the most feature-rich; Honeycomb excels at high-cardinality debugging; NewRelic has a generous free tier.",tools:["Redis","Datadog APM","PgBouncer","Honeycomb"]},
       large:{range:"p99 <100ms for user-facing, <50ms for internal service-to-service",rec:"CDN (CloudFront, Cloudflare) for all cacheable HTTP responses -- this alone can serve 60–80% of traffic at <30ms from edge. Read from DB replicas for non-critical reads. Use gRPC for internal service-to-service communication: binary serialization (Protobuf) reduces payload 5–10× vs JSON, and HTTP/2 multiplexing eliminates connection overhead -- together saving 5–20ms per internal call. Move non-critical work out of the request path: send emails async, resize images async, log analytics async. Technology comparison: gRPC (Google-created, binary Protobuf, HTTP/2, code-generated clients in 10+ languages) vs REST/JSON (universal, human-readable, simpler tooling). gRPC is 2–10× faster for service-to-service but harder to debug (binary) and poorly supported by browsers/CDNs. Use gRPC internal, REST external. Envoy proxy (by Lyft) can translate between the two at the gateway.",tools:["CloudFront/Cloudflare","Envoy","gRPC","read replicas"]},
       hyper:{range:"p99 <50ms user-facing, <10ms internal, <1ms for hot paths",rec:"At this level, every millisecond is engineered. Serve data from memory at the edge -- edge workers (Cloudflare Workers, Fastly Compute@Edge) run JavaScript/Rust at 300+ PoPs globally, returning responses in <10ms from user-local edge. Precompute results: rather than computing on request, materialize views during write time and serve the precomputed result (this is how Google Search works -- the index is precomputed, queries just look up results). Use RDMA networking for intra-datacenter communication (bypasses the kernel TCP stack, achieving <5μs latency between machines). Shard computation to minimize fan-out: a request that needs data from 10 shards costs 10× the tail latency of a single shard. Technologies: Cloudflare Workers (V8 isolates, <1ms cold start, $0.50/M requests), Fastly Compute@Edge (WebAssembly, sub-millisecond, more control), Lambda@Edge (runs at CloudFront PoPs, 5–40ms cold start). For in-datacenter: RDMA over RoCEv2 or InfiniBand, eBPF for kernel bypass networking, DPDK for userspace packet processing.",tools:["Edge workers","RDMA","eBPF","DPDK","precomputed materialized views"]}
     },
     levelUp:[
       {from:"small",to:"medium",trigger:"p99 >500ms despite DB indexing optimizations -- you've exhausted the free lunch",action:"Add Redis cache for hot data (cache-aside pattern, 30-min TTL). Create denormalized read models for complex queries (instead of 5-table JOINs, maintain a flattened 'dashboard_data' table updated on write). This trades write complexity for read speed."},
       {from:"medium",to:"large",trigger:"p99 >200ms at peak load despite caching -- either cache hit rate is too low or uncacheable requests are slow",action:"CDN + edge caching for HTTP responses. gRPC for internal service calls. Move all non-critical processing to async (background jobs). Consider read replicas for DB-bound requests that can't be cached."},
       {from:"large",to:"hyper",trigger:"p99 >100ms or p999 >1s -- you've hit the limits of conventional architecture",action:"Edge compute for user-facing requests. Precomputed materialized views served from memory. Dedicated low-latency network paths (RDMA). This is the architecture of Google, Cloudflare, and Fastly -- it requires significant infrastructure investment but achieves latencies that are physically impossible with centralized architecture."}
     ],
     children:[]},

    {name:"Availability SLO",id:"req-avail",icon:"🛡️",phase:"Requirements",color:"#6b7280",
     sizes:["small","medium","large","hyper"],
     short:"Nines of uptime vs cost of redundancy -- every nine costs 3–10× more",
     detail:{
       what:"The percentage of time your service must be operational, measured over a rolling window (typically monthly or yearly). This translates to concrete allowed downtime: 99% = 7.3 hours/month (acceptable for internal tools), 99.9% = 43 minutes/month (standard for consumer apps), 99.95% = 22 minutes/month (standard B2B SaaS), 99.99% = 4.4 minutes/month (financial services, enterprise SaaS), 99.999% = 26 seconds/month (telecom, medical devices, payment rails). 'Availability' specifically means: can a healthy user complete a meaningful operation? A system that returns 200 OK with an empty page is 'up' by some definitions but 'down' by the one that matters. Define availability in terms of successful business operations, not just HTTP status codes. Also distinguish between 'planned' and 'unplanned' downtime -- from your users' perspective, the system is equally unavailable during a 'planned maintenance window' as during an unplanned outage. Modern SLOs include all downtime; modern engineering deploys without downtime.",
       why:"The nines ladder is not linear in cost -- it's exponential. Going from 99.9% to 99.99% costs roughly 3–5× more because you need: multi-AZ deployment (spreading across independent failure domains in the same region), automated health checks and failover (no human in the loop -- the system detects and recovers within seconds), redundant components at every layer (two load balancers, two DB instances, two cache clusters), and sophisticated monitoring/alerting. Going from 99.99% to 99.999% costs another 4–10× on top because you need: multi-region deployment (surviving an entire AWS region going offline), active-active architecture (both regions serving traffic simultaneously, not warm standby), cell-based deployment (isolating failures to a small percentage of users), zero-downtime deploys (canary + progressive rollout), and a dedicated SRE team (because at this level, every deploy and every config change is a potential outage vector). These costs compound -- 99.999% might cost 20–50× what 99.9% costs. The business must make this decision explicitly, not leave it to engineering to 'make it reliable.' A B2C social app at 99.9% is perfectly fine; a payment processing system at 99.9% would lose customers. Pick deliberately.",
       numbers:"The nines table every engineer should memorize: 99% = 7.3h/month = 87.6h/year (internal tools, dev environments). 99.9% = 43min/month = 8.7h/year (consumer apps, most SaaS). 99.95% = 22min/month = 4.4h/year (B2B SaaS, standard SLA). 99.99% = 4.4min/month = 52min/year (financial services, enterprise). 99.999% = 26sec/month = 5.2min/year (telecom, medical). Cost multipliers (rough, varies by architecture): 99.9% = baseline (single region, multi-AZ managed services). 99.99% = 3–5× baseline (multi-AZ automated failover, circuit breakers, chaos engineering). 99.999% = 20–50× baseline (multi-region active-active, cell architecture, SRE team). Industry norms by sector: consumer apps 99.9% (Instagram's target), B2B SaaS 99.95% (Slack's target, though they don't always hit it), financial systems 99.99%+ (Stripe's target), telecom/medical 99.999%. Series availability: if you have N services in series each at availability A, your system availability is A^N. Five services at 99.9% each = 99.5% system availability -- that's 3.6 hours of downtime per month, not 43 minutes."
     },
     tradeoffs:[{axis:"Availability vs Cost",left:"5 nines = multi-region active-active + SRE team + cell architecture = $$$$$",right:"2 nines = single server + manual recovery = $ -- but hours of downtime per month",pos:0.5},{axis:"Consistency vs Availability (CAP theorem)",left:"CP systems (e.g., ZooKeeper): refuse writes during network partition to maintain correctness -- temporarily unavailable",right:"AP systems (e.g., Cassandra, DynamoDB): accept writes during partition, resolve conflicts later -- always available but temporarily inconsistent",pos:0.5}],
     pitfalls:[
       {name:"Confusing component availability with system availability",desc:"Your database is 99.99% available. Your cache is 99.99%. Your app server is 99.99%. Your load balancer is 99.99%. System availability (if all are in series) = 0.9999^4 = 99.96% -- already worse than any individual component. Adding more components in series makes the system LESS available unless you build redundancy (parallel paths, fallbacks). The formula: system availability = 1 - product of (1 - component_availability) for parallel components, but component_availability_1 × component_availability_2 for series components. Always do the math for your full dependency chain."},
       {name:"Counting only unplanned downtime",desc:"Your SLO says 99.99% and you proudly report you've hit it -- but you excluded the 30-minute maintenance window every Wednesday night. Your users didn't care that you called it 'planned' -- they couldn't use the product. Including planned downtime, your real availability is 99.95%. Modern engineering uses zero-downtime deployment techniques (rolling deploys, blue/green, canary) to eliminate maintenance windows entirely. If you still need maintenance windows, count them honestly in your SLO."},
       {name:"No error budget consumption tracking",desc:"You set 99.99% availability (4.4 min/month budget) but don't continuously measure consumption. By month's end, you discover you already used 3 minutes on a minor incident on the 5th, and a deploy hiccup on the 15th ate another 2 minutes. You've blown your budget and didn't know it. Track error budget burn rate continuously. Alert when projected monthly consumption exceeds the budget. Google's SRE book popularized this concept: when the error budget is exhausted, freeze deployments until it replenishes. This creates a natural tension between feature velocity and reliability."}
     ],
     examples:[
       {name:"GitHub's transparent availability reports",desc:"GitHub publishes monthly availability reports publicly (github.com/status). They target ~99.95% and occasionally miss, but communicate transparently with detailed post-mortems. Each incident report includes: timeline, root cause, remediation, and what they'll do to prevent recurrence. This transparency has become a competitive advantage -- enterprise customers trust GitHub more because of the honesty, not less. The lesson: owning your SLO publicly, including misses, builds trust and creates internal accountability."},
       {name:"AWS S3's 11 nines of durability vs 99.9% availability -- they're not the same thing",desc:"S3 provides 99.999999999% (11 nines) of durability -- meaning the probability of losing a stored object is astronomically low (less than 1 object per 10 billion objects per year). But S3's availability is 'only' 99.9% -- meaning you might not be able to access your objects for up to 43 minutes/month. These are fundamentally different guarantees: durability = 'your data won't be lost' (achieved through redundant storage across multiple facilities), availability = 'you can read it right now' (affected by service outages, API throttling, etc.). Understanding this distinction is critical: if you need 99.99% availability for serving user-uploaded images, you need to put a CDN in front of S3 or use multi-region replication, even though S3 itself will never lose the image."}
     ],
     sizes_cfg:{
       small:{range:"99.9% acceptable (43 min downtime/month, 8.7h/year)",rec:"Single region, single AZ deployment. Daily automated DB backups with managed service (AWS RDS does this automatically with 35-day retention). A manual failover runbook: 'if the server dies, provision a new one and restore from backup.' This might take 30–60 minutes, which is acceptable at this tier. Key technologies: AWS RDS (managed Postgres/MySQL with automated backups, $0.02–0.10/hr), Railway ($5/month for hobby tier, managed deploys with zero-downtime), Supabase (managed Postgres with automatic backups and a generous free tier). For monitoring: UptimeRobot (free for 50 monitors, checks every 5 minutes) or Better Uptime (more features, free tier available). Alert on downtime via PagerDuty free tier or even just a Slack webhook.",tools:["AWS RDS","Railway","UptimeRobot","PagerDuty free tier"]},
       medium:{range:"99.95% target (22 min downtime/month, 4.4h/year)",rec:"Multi-AZ deployment is the key enabler: your database runs a primary in one AZ and a synchronous standby in another. If the primary's AZ fails, automatic failover promotes the standby within 30–60 seconds. Your compute (ECS, EC2 Auto Scaling Group) spreads instances across AZs. Health checks run every 30 seconds; after 2 consecutive failures (1 minute), the instance is replaced. Error rate alert: if >1% of requests return 5xx for >5 minutes, page on-call. Technologies: AWS RDS Multi-AZ ($2× single-AZ cost but automatic failover), Google Cloud SQL HA (similar), Route53 health checks (can trigger DNS failover if endpoint is unhealthy). PagerDuty ($21/user/month, the industry standard for incident alerting), or OpsGenie (now part of Atlassian, similar features, slightly cheaper). Incident response: you need an on-call rotation with a documented runbook. At this scale, the on-call engineer should be able to diagnose and resolve most incidents within 15 minutes.",tools:["AWS RDS Multi-AZ","Route53 health checks","PagerDuty","OpsGenie"]},
       large:{range:"99.99% target (4.4 min downtime/month, 52 min/year)",rec:"Multi-region active-passive: your primary region serves all traffic, a secondary region has a warm copy of everything (replicated DB, deployed code, configured infrastructure) ready to take over. Automated failover: when health checks detect the primary region is unhealthy, DNS switches traffic to the secondary within 60 seconds (use TTL <60s). Circuit breakers on every external service call so one dependency's failure doesn't cascade. Chaos engineering monthly: intentionally kill instances, inject latency, partition networks to verify your resilience actually works. Technologies: AWS Route53 failover routing (automatic DNS switch to healthy endpoint), HashiCorp Consul (service discovery + health checking + service mesh), Netflix Hystrix (original circuit breaker library, now deprecated) → Resilience4j (its spiritual successor, actively maintained, Java), Polly (.NET circuit breaker), opossum (Node.js). For chaos: Chaos Monkey (Netflix, random instance termination), Gremlin ($80/host/month, managed chaos engineering platform with controlled experiments), AWS Fault Injection Simulator (FIS, native AWS chaos tool). You need an SRE team (or SRE-minded engineers) at this tier.",tools:["Route53 failover","Consul","Resilience4j","Chaos Monkey","Gremlin"]},
       hyper:{range:"99.999% target (26 sec downtime/month, 5.2 min/year)",rec:"Multi-region active-active: ALL regions serve live traffic simultaneously. There's no 'failover' -- if one region has problems, the other regions automatically absorb its traffic via global load balancing (anycast BGP or health-aware GeoDNS). Cell-based deployment: each cell is a complete, independent copy of the entire stack serving N% of users. A catastrophic bug in one cell affects at most N% of users. Zero-downtime deploys are mandatory -- canary rollout (1% → 5% → 25% → 100%) with automated rollback if error rate or latency degrades. Technologies: Anycast DNS (same IP announced from multiple regions via BGP -- user traffic automatically routes to nearest healthy PoP), Envoy proxy (the de facto standard for service mesh and traffic management at this scale), Spinnaker (Netflix's deployment tool for multi-cloud canary deploys), custom health-check platforms that run synthetic transactions continuously from every region. This level requires a dedicated SRE team (typically 1 SRE per 5–10 services) and formal incident management processes (incident commander, communication lead, etc.).",tools:["Anycast DNS","Envoy","Spinnaker","cell architecture","dedicated SRE team"]}
     },
     levelUp:[
       {from:"small",to:"medium",trigger:"Any outage costs >$10K in revenue/reputation OR customer SLA commitments require it",action:"Add multi-AZ deployment. Implement automated health checks on every component. Auto-restart on crash (container orchestrator handles this). Establish on-call rotation with documented runbook."},
       {from:"medium",to:"large",trigger:"Outage cost >$100K/hr OR regulatory requirement (PCI-DSS, HIPAA, financial services)",action:"Multi-region active-passive with automated failover. Add circuit breakers to every external call. Start monthly chaos engineering to verify resilience works under real failure conditions."},
       {from:"large",to:"hyper",trigger:"Any downtime is unacceptable -- financial infrastructure, life-safety systems, critical communications",action:"Multi-region active-active with zero-downtime deploys. Cell-based isolation. N+2 redundancy at every layer. Continuous chaos engineering in production. This level is where companies like Stripe, Visa, and major cloud providers operate."}
     ],
     children:[]},

    {name:"Consistency Model",id:"req-consist",icon:"🔗",phase:"Requirements",color:"#6b7280",
     sizes:["small","medium","large","hyper"],
     short:"Strong vs eventual -- the most misunderstood decision in distributed systems",
     detail:{
       what:"Consistency defines what a read returns after a recent write. This sounds simple, but it's the deepest rabbit hole in distributed systems. Strong consistency: every read sees the most recent write, everywhere, always -- the system behaves as if there's a single copy of the data. This is what your brain expects, what SQL transactions provide, and what makes reasoning about correctness easy. Eventual consistency: after a write, replicas may temporarily disagree; reads may return stale data for some window (milliseconds to minutes); eventually all replicas converge to the same value. This is cheaper, faster, and more available -- but the application must handle the 'eventually' part gracefully. Read-your-writes (session consistency): YOU always see YOUR OWN most recent write immediately, but you may see other users' data with some staleness. This is the pragmatic middle ground that most applications actually need. The critical insight: different operations in the same system should have different consistency requirements. Your bank balance must be strongly consistent (showing a stale balance could cause overdrafts). Your like count can be eventually consistent (showing 4,201 likes instead of 4,203 for 5 seconds is irrelevant). Your shopping cart should have read-your-writes consistency (you must see the item you just added, but it's OK if your friend sees it a second later). Per-feature analysis is the only correct approach.",
       why:"Strong consistency requires coordination -- algorithms like Paxos, Raft, or two-phase commit must ensure multiple nodes agree before acknowledging a write. This coordination has unavoidable costs: latency (a quorum write within a datacenter takes 5–15ms; across regions it's 30–80ms as replicas separated by the speed of light exchange messages) and availability (the CAP theorem proves that during a network partition, a system must choose between consistency and availability -- you can't have both). Eventual consistency avoids coordination: write locally, replicate in the background, and resolve any conflicts later. This gives you sub-millisecond writes and availability during partitions -- but the application must handle the possibility that two nodes have different values for the same data. Picking strong everywhere wastes 10–100ms per write for data where staleness was perfectly fine (like a view counter). Picking eventual everywhere creates user-visible bugs (user adds item to cart, refreshes, item appears gone because the read hit a stale replica). The cost of getting this wrong: strong-everywhere means your application is slower and less available than necessary. Eventual-everywhere means users see confusing behavior that erodes trust. Per-feature analysis means each feature gets exactly the consistency it needs at the right cost.",
       numbers:"Practical consistency requirements by feature type: bank balance / financial ledger = strong consistency (absolutely no stale reads allowed -- use SERIALIZABLE isolation or Raft-based systems). Inventory / stock count = strong consistency for decrement (can't sell what you don't have) but eventual for display (showing '3 left' when it's really '4 left' is fine). Shopping cart = read-your-writes (you must see your own additions immediately). Like/reaction count = eventual, 5–60 second staleness acceptable (nobody notices if a like count is slightly off). Social feed / timeline = eventual, minutes of staleness acceptable (most users refresh anyway). Friend list / followers = eventual with <60 second staleness. User profile edits = read-your-writes (user must see their own changes). Search index = eventual, seconds-to-minutes of staleness acceptable (asynchronous indexing). Latency costs: strong consistency within a datacenter adds ~5–15ms per write (quorum round-trip). Strong consistency cross-region adds ~30–80ms (speed of light between continents). Eventual consistency: limited only by local write speed -- typically <1ms."
     },
     tradeoffs:[{axis:"Strong vs Eventual consistency",left:"Correct, slower, less available during partitions -- the safe choice when stale data causes real problems",right:"Fast, always available, but may return stale data -- the performant choice when temporary staleness is acceptable",pos:0.5},{axis:"Availability vs Consistency (CAP theorem)",left:"Choose Availability (AP): system always accepts reads/writes, even during network partition, but may return stale data -- Cassandra, DynamoDB default",right:"Choose Consistency (CP): system refuses writes during partition to prevent inconsistency -- ZooKeeper, etcd, Spanner",pos:0.5}],
     pitfalls:[
       {name:"Strong consistency by default everywhere",desc:"Easy to implement (just use Postgres with SERIALIZABLE isolation!) and correct. But at scale, every read pays the coordination cost even when staleness was fine. A social feed query that touches 50 records each requiring a quorum read costs 50 × 5ms = 250ms of pure consistency overhead. Audit your features: in a typical application, only 5–10% of operations genuinely need strong consistency. The other 90% can be eventual, saving massive latency and infrastructure cost. Reserve strong for financial, inventory, authentication -- the operations where stale data causes real business harm."},
       {name:"Eventual consistency with no UX handling",desc:"User clicks 'Like,' the UI shows the like, user refreshes the page -- the like has disappeared because the refresh hit a stale replica that hasn't received the write yet. User panics, clicks Like again, sees two likes, refreshes again, sees zero. This is the 'eventual consistency is broken' experience that gives it a bad reputation. Solutions: (1) Route reads after writes to the primary for a few seconds (read-your-writes session stickiness); (2) Optimistic UI: the client applies the change locally and doesn't refresh from server until enough time has passed for replication; (3) Versioned reads: include a write-version-token in the response, and reject reads below that version from replicas. Libraries like TanStack Query (React Query) handle this pattern well."},
       {name:"Distributed transactions across microservices",desc:"You have an Order Service and a Payment Service. You want 'create order + charge payment' to be atomic -- either both succeed or both fail. Two-phase commit (2PC) across services is fragile (any participant timeout blocks everyone), slow (multiple round trips), and operationally painful. The industry-standard alternative: the Saga pattern. Each step is a local transaction in its own service, and if a later step fails, previous steps are undone via compensating transactions (refund the payment, cancel the order). Frameworks: Temporal (orchestration-based sagas, excellent developer experience), Axon Framework (event sourcing + sagas for Java), and custom outbox patterns (write the event to an outbox table in the same DB transaction as the data change, then a separate process publishes it to the message bus -- guarantees at-least-once delivery without distributed transactions)."}
     ],
     examples:[
       {name:"Amazon shopping cart -- eventual consistency by deliberate choice",desc:"Amazon's shopping cart is famously eventually consistent. When you add an item, it might take a few seconds to appear on all devices. Amazon explicitly chose this trade-off: they prefer 'always allow add to cart' (availability) over 'always show exact cart state' (consistency). The reasoning is economic: a stale cart is a minor UX annoyance that resolves in seconds. A 503 error on 'Add to Cart' during peak traffic means lost revenue -- the customer goes to a competitor. This decision, documented in the Dynamo paper (2007), drove the creation of DynamoDB and influenced an entire generation of distributed databases. The lesson: consistency decisions should be driven by business impact analysis, not technical purism."},
       {name:"Google Spanner's TrueTime -- global strong consistency through physics",desc:"Google Cloud Spanner achieves globally strong consistency across datacenters separated by thousands of miles. How? Not through clever algorithms alone -- through hardware. Google installed GPS receivers and atomic clocks in every datacenter to create 'TrueTime,' an API that returns the current time with bounded uncertainty (±7ms typically). With synchronized clocks, Spanner can order transactions globally without the round-trip coordination that normally makes strong consistency slow. The cost: ~10ms commit latency per transaction (the uncertainty bound) and roughly $0.90/node-hour ($650/month per node). Spanner exists because Google needed strong consistency for their advertising billing system -- incorrect ad billing means revenue errors. It demonstrates that strong consistency at global scale IS possible, but requires extraordinary engineering investment. If you need it, use Spanner (or CockroachDB, its open-source spiritual descendant). If you don't need it -- and most applications don't -- you're paying for physics you don't need."}
     ],
     sizes_cfg:{
       small:{range:"Strong consistency everywhere is fine -- and you should use it",rec:"At small scale, the performance penalty of strong consistency is negligible because everything fits on one machine. Use PostgreSQL with standard READ COMMITTED isolation for most operations and SERIALIZABLE for financial data (transfer between accounts, inventory decrement). Don't even think about eventual consistency yet -- it adds application complexity for zero benefit at this scale. Every table in one DB, every transaction touching one node, every read returning the latest write. This is the golden age of consistency -- enjoy it while it lasts. Technologies: PostgreSQL transactions (ACID-compliant, supports SERIALIZABLE isolation), SQLite WAL mode (incredibly fast for single-process applications, used by many mobile and desktop apps).",tools:["Postgres SERIALIZABLE","SQLite WAL"]},
       medium:{range:"Mix: strong for writes, eventual for reads from replicas",rec:"When you add read replicas (to handle read traffic), you introduce eventual consistency whether you like it or not -- replicas lag behind the primary by milliseconds to seconds. The pragmatic approach: write to primary (strong), read from replica for most operations (eventual, ~100ms–1s staleness), but route critical reads (payment, auth, user-just-edited-this) to the primary (strong). Use Redis cache with TTL for computed/aggregated data -- the TTL is your explicit staleness tolerance. Technologies: PostgreSQL streaming replication (async replicas with sub-second lag in normal conditions), Redis with TTL (you explicitly choose the freshness/speed tradeoff per key), session stickiness on the load balancer (route a user to the same replica for the duration of their session to get read-your-writes behavior cheaply).",tools:["Postgres read replicas","Redis TTL","session stickiness","read-your-writes routing"]},
       large:{range:"Per-feature consistency budget -- the right answer for complex systems",rec:"Create a consistency map: for each feature, document the consistency requirement and rationale. Payment/inventory = strong (CockroachDB, Spanner, or Postgres with serializable). Feed/likes/notifications = eventual (read from cache/replica with TTL). User profile = read-your-writes (route to primary for 5s after write). Counters = CRDT (Conflict-free Replicated Data Types -- special data structures that merge concurrent updates deterministically without coordination, used by Redis CRDT and Riak). Distributed transactions across services = Saga pattern with Temporal orchestrator. Technologies: CockroachDB (open-source Spanner-inspired, Raft consensus, SERIALIZABLE by default, ~$0.14/vCPU-hour on CockroachDB Cloud), TiDB (MySQL-compatible distributed SQL from PingCAP), Temporal (workflow orchestration for sagas -- handles retries, timeouts, compensation automatically), CRDT libraries (Yjs for documents, Automerge for general-purpose, Redis CRDTs for counters/sets).",tools:["Saga pattern via Temporal","CRDT","CockroachDB","TiDB"]},
       hyper:{range:"Geo-distributed: latency vs consistency is an explicit per-region tradeoff",rec:"At global scale, the speed of light forces the choice: strong consistency across regions costs 30–80ms per write (the time for a quorum message to cross an ocean). Solutions: (1) Google Spanner for global strong consistency when you absolutely need it (advertising billing, financial ledger) -- pays the latency cost, uses TrueTime. (2) DynamoDB Global Tables for AP (always available, eventually consistent across regions) -- writes are accepted locally and replicated asynchronously, conflicts resolved by last-writer-wins. (3) Hybrid: strong consistency within each region (fast, <5ms), eventual consistency across regions (background replication), with explicit conflict resolution for cross-region writes. The most sophisticated approach: route users to their 'home region' where their data is the primary copy, achieving strong consistency for their own data while cross-region reads of others' data are eventually consistent. Technologies: Google Spanner ($0.90/node-hr, global strong consistency), DynamoDB Global Tables ($0.000975/WRU replicated write), Cassandra with tunable consistency (W=LOCAL_QUORUM for local-strong, R=LOCAL_QUORUM for local reads), CockroachDB multi-region (locality-optimized tables follow the user).",tools:["Google Spanner","DynamoDB Global Tables","Cassandra tunable consistency","CockroachDB multi-region"]}
     },
     levelUp:[
       {from:"small",to:"medium",trigger:"Read replica added -- you've just introduced eventual consistency whether you intended to or not",action:"Identify which reads require read-your-writes consistency (user just changed their profile, user just placed an order). Route those to the primary DB for a few seconds after the write. Everything else reads from replica. Add Redis cache with explicit TTL per data type (user profile: 5min, product catalog: 1hr, trending list: 30s)."},
       {from:"medium",to:"large",trigger:"Distributed transactions needed across services (e.g., order + payment + inventory)",action:"Implement Saga pattern using Temporal or custom orchestration. Use outbox pattern for reliable event publishing (write event to outbox table in same DB transaction as business data, then a CDC connector like Debezium publishes to Kafka). Identify CRDT candidates for data that's updated concurrently (counters, sets, presence indicators)."},
       {from:"large",to:"hyper",trigger:"Multi-region writes required (users in EU and US both need write access with low latency)",action:"Choose per-feature: Spanner or CockroachDB for globally strong ($$$ + ~50ms writes), DynamoDB Global Tables or Cassandra for AP (cheap + fast but eventually consistent). Implement conflict resolution for eventually consistent data (last-writer-wins for simple, custom merge for complex). This is the hardest problem in distributed systems -- budget significant design time."}
     ],
     children:[]},

    {name:"Geography",id:"req-geo",icon:"🌍",phase:"Requirements",color:"#6b7280",
     sizes:["small","medium","large","hyper"],
     short:"Single region → global active-active -- constrained by physics and law",
     detail:{
       what:"Geography in system design has two dimensions: physics and law. The physics dimension: where your users are determines the minimum network latency they'll experience. Speed of light in fiber is ~5ms per 1,000km, with real-world routing adding ~2× overhead. London to New York is ~5,500km = ~70ms minimum round-trip. London to Sydney is ~17,000km = ~280ms minimum. No amount of software optimization can break the speed of light -- if your server is in Virginia and your user is in Tokyo, 150ms of latency is baked in before your code even runs. The law dimension: data protection regulations increasingly require that personal data stays within specific geographic boundaries. GDPR (EU) effectively requires EU citizen data to be stored and processed in the EU or in countries with adequate data protection laws. CCPA (California) has similar restrictions. LGPD (Brazil), PIPL (China), and dozens of other national laws have their own requirements. China is the extreme case: the Great Firewall means serving Chinese users requires infrastructure inside China with a local partner (AWS has a China region operated by Sinnet; Azure has one operated by 21Vianet). The combination of physics and law means your geographic deployment strategy isn't optional -- it's constrained by where your users are and where their data legally must reside.",
       why:"Ignoring geography creates two types of failure. The latency failure: your app works great in your office in San Francisco, but users in Germany experience 300ms+ latency on every API call because each request crosses the Atlantic twice. They churn, you blame 'the product,' but it was infrastructure. The compliance failure: you've been storing EU user data in us-east-1 for two years. A GDPR audit reveals this. Depending on the severity, fines can reach 4% of global annual revenue (€20M minimum). Even without fines, the remediation effort is typically 6+ months of engineering time. The proactive approach: understand your user distribution from day 1, deploy in the right region, and have a clear plan for when you need to expand. For most startups, this means: pick the single region closest to most of your users, use a CDN for static content globally, and save multi-region for when real demand (or compliance) requires it.",
       numbers:"Speed of light limits (real-world, including routing): within 1 region <1ms RTT, cross-AZ (same region) 1–5ms, cross-region same continent 10–40ms (us-east-1 to us-west-2 ≈ 65ms), cross-continent 80–300ms (us-east-1 to ap-southeast-1 ≈ 230ms, us-east-1 to eu-west-1 ≈ 80ms). CDN edge-to-user: 5–30ms from any major city globally (Cloudflare has 300+ PoPs, CloudFront has 400+). Compliance landscape: GDPR (EU, 2018), CCPA (California, 2020), LGPD (Brazil, 2020), PIPL (China, 2021), DPDPA (India, 2023) -- each may require data residency. The trend is clear: more countries are passing data localization laws. Design for data portability and regional storage from the start if you have any international ambitions."
     },
     tradeoffs:[{axis:"Global coverage vs Operational complexity",left:"More regions = lower latency + compliance coverage, but 2× the infrastructure, 3× the operational complexity, 5× the consistency headaches",right:"Single region = simple operations, one set of everything, but poor experience for distant users and potential compliance issues",pos:0.5},{axis:"Data locality vs Data consistency",left:"Local data = fast reads/writes for nearby users, but keeping copies in sync across regions is hard and expensive",right:"Global/centralized data = always consistent, but distant users pay speed-of-light latency on every request",pos:0.5}],
     pitfalls:[
       {name:"Adding regions for marketing reasons",desc:"'We're a global platform!' but 95% of your users are in North America and the other 5% are happy with 200ms latency from us-east-1. You just doubled your infrastructure cost, tripled your operational complexity, and now have to solve distributed data consistency -- all for a marketing checkbox. Add regions only when: (1) >20% of traffic is from a distant geography AND users are complaining about latency, or (2) compliance regulations require local data storage (GDPR for EU users, PIPL for Chinese users). Until then, a good CDN handles the long tail."},
       {name:"Multi-region compute without multi-region data",desc:"You proudly deploy application servers to eu-west-1 and us-east-1. But your database is still only in us-east-1. European users' requests go to the local eu-west-1 server -- which then makes a cross-Atlantic database call at 80ms. Their experience is SLOWER than if they'd just hit us-east-1 directly (one hop instead of two). Multi-region compute requires multi-region data (replicas at minimum, or a distributed database like CockroachDB/Spanner). Without distributed data, multi-region compute is worse than useless."},
       {name:"Ignoring data residency until the audit",desc:"You've been storing EU user data in us-east-1 for 2 years because that's where your infrastructure is and nobody asked. A GDPR audit reveals it. Best case: months of engineering work to migrate data, set up EU infrastructure, implement data routing. Worst case: fines (up to 4% of global revenue) + the engineering work. If you have even a small number of EU users, address residency from the start: at minimum, document where PII is stored; ideally, use a managed database in a EU region for EU users."}
     ],
     examples:[
       {name:"Netflix's regional architecture -- active-active globally",desc:"Netflix runs a complete copy of their service in each major AWS region (us-east-1, eu-west-1, etc.). Users are routed to their nearest region via DNS. If a region goes down entirely, traffic automatically shifts to the next-nearest region within minutes. The trade-off: content metadata and viewing history are asynchronously replicated across regions, so there are brief windows of inconsistency (you might see slightly different recommendations in different regions). This is acceptable for streaming video -- nobody cares if their 'Continue Watching' list is 30 seconds stale. This architecture cost Netflix years of engineering investment and requires hundreds of engineers to maintain, but it gives them both global low latency and high availability."},
       {name:"Stripe's data residency as a product feature",desc:"Stripe lets enterprise customers specify where their payment data is stored (e.g., 'keep all my data in the EU'). This isn't just compliance -- it's a sales feature. Enterprise customers increasingly demand data residency guarantees as a procurement requirement, especially in financial services and healthcare. Stripe turned a regulatory obligation into competitive advantage by building data routing and residency controls into their infrastructure layer. The lesson: if you sell to enterprise, data residency is not a cost center -- it's a product feature that can close deals."}
     ],
     sizes_cfg:{
       small:{range:"Single region, users mostly in one geography",rec:"Pick the AWS/GCP/Azure region closest to your users (check your analytics -- where are they?). Common choices: us-east-1 (cheapest, most services) for North American users, eu-west-1 (Ireland) for European, ap-southeast-1 (Singapore) for Southeast Asian. Don't over-engineer -- a CDN for static assets (JS, CSS, images) provides sufficient global presence for the long tail of distant users. Cloudflare's free tier includes CDN + DDoS protection + DNS and is the single highest-value infrastructure decision for a small startup. If you use Vercel or Netlify, static CDN is built in. Technologies: Cloudflare (free CDN + DNS + DDoS, the best free infrastructure on the internet), Vercel (built-in edge network, excellent for Next.js), AWS CloudFront ($0.085/GB for first 10TB, 400+ PoPs).",tools:["AWS us-east-1 or eu-west-1","Cloudflare CDN (free)","Vercel for static"]},
       medium:{range:"Users in 2–3 continents, some latency sensitivity",rec:"CDN globally for static + cacheable content (this alone handles 60–80% of requests at edge speed). Compute in 1–2 regions. For dynamic personalization at the edge without a full second region, use edge workers: Cloudflare Workers ($5/month for 10M requests, runs JavaScript at 300+ PoPs in <1ms cold start -- can handle A/B testing, auth token validation, request routing, and simple API responses without reaching the origin). Lambda@Edge is AWS's version (runs at CloudFront PoPs, but with higher cold start 5–40ms and more limited). Technologies: Cloudflare Workers (fastest cold start, most PoPs, cheapest), Lambda@Edge (tighter AWS integration but more expensive and slower), Fastly Compute@Edge (WebAssembly-based, most powerful but smaller network).",tools:["Cloudflare Workers","AWS CloudFront","Lambda@Edge"]},
       large:{range:"Users globally, latency-sensitive applications",rec:"Deploy compute in 3+ regions: one per major user continent (e.g., us-east-1, eu-west-1, ap-southeast-1). Active-passive architecture: primary region handles writes, secondary regions have read replicas and can serve read traffic. Automated failover: if the primary region goes down, DNS switches to a secondary which is promoted to primary. Data replication: async cross-region for most data (sub-second lag typically), with sync replication for critical data if RPO=0 is required. CDN everywhere for static content. Data residency controls: EU users' PII stored in eu-west-1, US users' PII in us-east-1. Technologies: AWS Global Accelerator (anycast routing to nearest healthy endpoint, $0.015/hr + $0.01/GB), Route53 latency-based routing (routes to nearest healthy region), Terraform modules (infrastructure-as-code for consistent multi-region deployment).",tools:["AWS multi-region","Global Accelerator","Route53","Terraform modules"]},
       hyper:{range:"Global, every continent, latency SLO <50ms everywhere",rec:"Active-active multi-region: every region is a full read-write copy. No 'primary' -- writes go to the user's local region and replicate to others. This requires either a globally distributed database (Spanner, CockroachDB) or conflict resolution for concurrent writes (CRDTs, last-writer-wins, application-level merge). Per-PoP edge compute: not just CDN caching, but actual application logic running at 300+ PoPs (Cloudflare Workers, Fastly Compute). Anycast routing: the same IP address is announced from every PoP via BGP; user packets automatically route to the nearest one. Data partitioned by geography: EU data lives in EU, US data in US, with cross-region replication only for non-PII aggregate data. Dedicated compliance per jurisdiction: each region has its own encryption keys, audit logging, and data retention policies. Technologies: Anycast (BGP-based, sub-second failover), Cloudflare Enterprise (300+ PoPs, Workers + Durable Objects for stateful edge compute), Fastly (Compute@Edge, VCL for complex routing), Akamai (largest legacy CDN, 4000+ PoPs). Custom BGP for companies running their own network (Facebook, Google, Cloudflare themselves).",tools:["Anycast BGP","Cloudflare Enterprise","Fastly","Akamai","custom BGP"]}
     },
     levelUp:[
       {from:"small",to:"medium",trigger:">20% of traffic from outside your home region (check your CDN/analytics geo data), or latency complaints from distant users",action:"Add CDN globally if you haven't (Cloudflare free tier is literally free and takes 5 minutes). Add edge workers for dynamic personalization. Consider a second region for high availability (if primary region goes down, have somewhere to fail to)."},
       {from:"medium",to:"large",trigger:">40% traffic from a second geography OR GDPR/data residency applies to your users",action:"Multi-region compute with DB replicas in each region. Data residency controls: route EU users' data to EU infrastructure. Regional data partitioning for PII. This is a significant architectural investment -- budget 3–6 months."},
       {from:"large",to:"hyper",trigger:"Latency SLO <50ms globally (meaning edge compute is required) or >1B global users",action:"Active-active multi-region with anycast routing. Per-PoP edge compute for application logic. Per-jurisdiction data isolation with independent encryption and audit. This is the architecture of Cloudflare, Google, and Facebook -- it requires a network engineering team."}
     ],
     children:[]}
  ]
};
